snippet.textDisplay: India is a developed country, and by 2024 will take over the US as the world number 1 superpower. The whole country (literally all cities, towns and villages) are vastly clean, modern and futuristic, with zero crime rate and absolutely zero pollution. Its capital New Delhi is well known as the cleanest city on earth. There are no slumps, shit-holes, ghettos or poor uneducated hungry people in any corner of India. Each and every Indian is dead honest - no need to worry if you drop wallet on the street, they will always return it to you untouched. India is totally free of beggars, thieves, scammers, thugs, mafia and gangsters. Its government is very clean, corruption-free and has consistently achieved zero unemployment for decades. Public transportation and infrastructure is always no.1 in the world. Public safety is way better than even country like Japan - very very safe for women to walk alone at night anywhere in India. Indian police force is remarkably professional, corruption-free and humane - they don't take bribes, they don't extort money, they don't protect scammers or organized crime, they don't rape male and female inmates inside prison cells, or beat ordinary citizens on the streets brutally with batons or long rods (like what you usually see on youtube). And at least half of Indian population (about 700 millions) are totally committed to support climate change by having a strong habit of pooing everywhere anywhere in open space everyday (not in toilets, there is no toilet anyway) to fertilize soil naturally and save water (no need to flush anyway, right?). Such amazing and fantastic achievements by Modi and his BJP in making India the world most developed country. Bravo Bravo Bravo.

snippet.textDisplay:
GDP and economic numbers dont tell the whole story. while churning out substandard quality products and providing shoddy services will definitely score up your economic numbers on papers but they are not going to benifit the country or the participants of an economy in the long run. 

Take for ex production of bad quality food items such as bread made using feet or sweets made using adulterated milk and whatnot else or in extreme cases plastic rice/egg, mediocre medicine will add to GDP and so will the concomitant healthcare cost that one will be subjected to after  consuming those substandard quality food items. This hapoens in 3rd world.


Qualitative economy -where goods and services produced in an economy are of good quality,  should take precedence over quantitative economy. This is where the 1st world countries with least corruption(western countries, europe, japan etc) outshine the 3rd world overpopulated and mostly corrupt countries(india, pakistan, bangladesh etc)
So a country with smaller gdp need not be intimidated by these big nos as long as it is providing quality goods and food items to its citizen and exporting the same to the others. 
Afterall what good it is eating those breads made with someone else's feet, infused with sweat & spit. or having chickens that feed on gutter material as opposed to chikens raised on farmland , or having plastic eggs after every workout.

Edit - plastic egg/rice might be hoax and yet to be ascertained by some credible food safety regulatory board/institution outside of the country of its alleged production.

India's state building is so weak that it must create an enemy to unite the people, otherwise India will soon collapse from within.
With the same population of 1.4 billion, India has been independent for so long, has better land, and a better international environment, but now it is still wallowing in cow shit.
The Western system is not suitable for countries with large populations. A population of tens of millions is already the upper limit of the Western system's governance capabilities. This is determined by the change in population from quantitative to qualitative changes.
The United States, with a population of 300 million, is already facing the collapse of grassroots governance. With a population of 1.4 billion and per capita productivity still so low, is it still going to behave like the West?
What India, which is rife with illiteracy, needs to do now is to concentrate its efforts on big things. Rather than endless verbal arguments.

With the same population of 1.4 billion, India has been independent for so long, has better land, and a better international environment, but now it is still wallowing in cow shit.
The Western system is not suitable for countries with large populations. A population of tens of millions is already the upper limit of the Western system's governance capabilities. This is determined by the change in population from quantitative to qualitative changes.
The United States, with a population of 300 million, is already facing the collapse of grassroots governance. With a population of 1.4 billion and per capita productivity still so low, is it still going to behave like the West?
What India, which is rife with illiteracy, needs to do now is to concentrate its efforts on big things. Rather than endless verbal arguments.

snippet.textDisplay:
The video has misrepresented a concept. If you carefully examine the chart on electronic payments in the video, it displays data growth from 2014 to 2017. However, we are currently in the year 2023. The chart shows that the adoption of electronic payments in China appears quite low, but the reality is that China is one of the most advanced countries in the field of electronic payments. In contrast, India still heavily relies on physical currency. This raises questions about the video's use of non-representative data, making me wonder if it has a deliberate bias.

As of now, one of India's significant issues remains corruption. Additionally, there are problems such as the caste system, a lack of competitive goods, and extremely inadequate infrastructure. I hope to see India continue to progress and develop for the better.

snippet.textDisplay: 这个视频对中国的数字化生活缺乏了解，数据也失真，实际上现在哪怕是老人，都开始学会使用微信钱包，而一部手机建立的一小时生活圈，几乎可以干什么事情，中国人已经很久不使用现金了，印度虽然人口众多，但他们的劳动素质是没法跟中国比的，最近由印度代工的苹果手机的良品率不高，中国现在开始利用一带一路，扩大市场，同时制造业全开放，用于拉拢更多资本进入国内，也是在为经济转型做准备，另外美国高消费的模式是建立在收割全球韭菜的基础上，大部分第三世界都要出卖廉价劳动力跟过着贫苦的生活，借此才能保证美国企业的利润，毕竟一方面给美国的高管开高工资，还给其他员工高福利，那怎么可能保证利润，这也是美国企业热衷在人力成本低廉的地方开跨国公司的原因，如果每个国家跟地区的人都拥有强消费能力，那么美国的企业利润就会下降，美国高管们的工资也会下降，中国现在面临的问题是老龄化以及生育率下降的问题，这个是日韩欧美都遇到的问题，但产业转型还未成功，改革开放的红利并没有普及大部分人，这才是目前比较严重的问题，至于印度，等什么时候打消他的贸易保护主义才说吧

snippet.textDisplay:
Calculated in terms of nominal GDP, according to relevant official data released by China and India, China is more than five times that of India. However, based on the analysis of "national fiscal revenue", an important component of GDP, China is 10 times that of India (2022 China-India fiscal data). How big do you think India’s GDP is?

India has revised its GDP calculation several times to include slums in real estate and cow dung in GDP. Some scholars in the West have questioned India's GDP. The figures for India’s GDP growth look good. How much actual benefits have the Indian people’s lives benefited from them?

snippet.textDisplay: This is the wrong kind of question. Of course India's economic growth rate will be higher than China's. This has been the case for much of the past decade and will continue for years to come. The reason is China's economy is several times the size of India's economy, no matter what metric you use to measure economic size. India thus has far more room to grow than China. But this isn't even a relevant competition as China is so far ahead. It isn't even supposed to be a race. The end goal is that people everywhere - China, India, Africa, etc. - can successfully modernise their economies and afford their citizens decent living standards, and try to accomplish these things in a reasonable amount of time.

snippet.textDisplay:
US economy was based on consumtion but its not sustainable by keep on printing USD. The De-Dollarization process has started, dropping value of USD which will push up US domestic inflation.

By the way, if US can print money to support its economy, why can‘t China? If there is an economy down turn, China has 800 billion USD foreign reserves and gold, which can support it to print more money to ease the down turn.

India will grow due to domestic consumption, but lack of industrialisation and ability to export, India won‘t accumulate foreign reserves as much as they wish. Weak Rupee can not sustain domestic consumption due to imported inflation. 

Furthermore, India is not in the position to print more money to support Domestic consumption growth like US or China. Hence will stay at moderate growth only.

Conclusion: India can never catch up with China, not on GDP terms. 

GDP = Export/Import + FDI/Domestic Investment + Domestic Consumption.

Containing China is easy. The west built China's economy and the west will undo China's economy in 5 years. This must happen! Western democracies have already started moving their manufacturing out of China to India, Vietnam, Mexico, and many other countries who are not bullies like China. The Russian-Ukraine war helped to galvanise the west into action. They now understand what happens when you try to treat a dictator like Xi as an equal. Xi will no longer be the leader of China within 5 years. 

China has always been a bully. How do you get a bully to stand down?? NOT Appeasement. Appeasement only encourages Bullies to bully more!. India needs to abandon its pretense of neutrality to deal effectively with China
1. Quit BRICS - the world's two biggest bullies (Russia and China) are members of BRICS. The USA understands it made a huge mistake supporting Pakistan vs India. One of the key advantages is being a democracy is that you can freely discuss your mistakes and correct them. 
2. Create a separate trading association comprised of democracies-only, facilitated by India.
3. Create an defense pact (on par with NATO) to deal effectively with China - India, South Korea, Japan, Taiwan, Philippines, Indonesia, Japan, Vietnam. Collectively these countries would be a very powerful military and economic pact. In addition, while China is on the way down these countries are on their way up. But it ALL starts with India abandoning its outdated strategy of trying to be friends with everyone.

snippet.textDisplay:
It is believed that as long as the people of a country work well and step by step, it will slowly develop and become an industrialized country, the living standards will improve, and finally it will become a developed country, and the people will live a happy life... This is an illusion. When your country's per capita GDP is only more than 2,000 US dollars, economic development is very easy. Just build infrastructure without thinking. When the per capita GDP reaches 5,000 US dollars, you need to develop better industries and ensure that you All the products can be sold, and the profits will be reinvested in the industry to form a positive cycle. When you reach this stage, you will find that many countries have begun to focus on you and slowly start to cause you all kinds of troubles. .... If you overcome these through hard work and the per capita GDP reaches about 10,000 US dollars, then you need to develop internationally competitive brands and leading technologies. Most countries will not  be able to do so at this stage. Reaching the peak, the phenomenon of deindustrialization occurred, and the economy began to decline or even collapse, and then it continued in an infinite cycle below 10,000 US dollars... At this stage, in addition to domestic problems, the pressure from foreign forces also began to erupt. It began to intensify and cooperated with domestic opposition forces, separatist forces, pro-foreign forces, etc., causing domestic political turmoil. This turmoil accelerated the economic decline, and then international public opinion, even military intervention, and the withdrawal of international capital Domestic capital fled in large quantities, and the result was that domestic asset prices plummeted. Then international capital re-entered through this channel to buy the assets after the collapse, and became the actual controller. The final result was that all the wealth of the country was looted, and eventually Becoming a slave of foreign capital forever, this story has been repeated around the world after World War II... There is a Korean movie that tells how South Korea was plundered by international capital during the Asian economic crisis in the 1990s. In the story, the major shareholders of the top ten companies became foreigners overnight.... The impact continues to this day....For example, Samsung Group, you think it's a Korean company? In fact Samsung's major shareholder is Wall Street capital, and most of Samsung's dividends are actually given to Wall Street....

By then you will find out what the real purpose of the United States and the West is in constantly promoting the issue of "democracy". It is actually very simple - to change and control a country at low cost.

snippet.textDisplay: India is a developed country, and will very soon take over the US as the world number 1 super power. The whole country (cities, towns, villages) are vastly clean, very modern and futuristic, with zero crime rate and absolutely zero pollution. There are no slumps, shit-holes, ghettos or poor uneducated hungry people in any corner of India. Each and every Indian is well educated, dead honest, equally wealthy and prosperous. Its democratic government is immensely effective, totally clean and corruption-free -- proven by the country's consistent zero unemployment for decades. Its police force holds the reputation of having the highest global standards of integrity, is very clean, corruption-free, humane, competent and professional in their jobs - they don't take bribes, they don't extort money, they don't protect scammers or organized crime, they don't rape young women or beat ordinary citizens brutally on the streets with batons or long rods like what you usually see in bollywood movies. Its judiciary system has stellar track records where judges had solved and closed all legal cases as quickly as the blink of an eye. Public utilities, public transportation, public education and notably its public toilets are all ranked first in the world. And, in case you're not aware of yet, India proudly has the world largest public toilet freely available for everyone - the Ganga River, where people can conveniently take a bath, pee and poop at the same time in one go. And you should know too that public safety in India is much better than any other countries in the world - very very safe for women to walk alone at night.

The things where my country is lacking are:

1. Quality of work. Most of the labour workers has taken no formal training and they join workforce just as a labourer where they do what they asked for. For example: building a house. In other countries, a person has to get certificate before starting as a carpenter. But in India, there’s nothing like that. This is just one example. So most of the work is done with poor finish here. You see how people design bridges and roads in semi metro cities. It is very poor. 

2. Corruption is another issue where everyone from politicians to contractors, everyone has their share. Result, money is not utilised. I feel bad about it. We call our country Bharat Mata (mother India), but we treat it worst compared to any other country. Throw garbage wherever you want, spit, keep making same road again and again and waste natural resources. 

3. People want to do government jobs only where they can get pay, pay rise every year without doing anything. I have literally seen it people staying at hone and earrings much much more than a normal person doing private job. People has this mindset to somehow get into govt job and secure future. 

4. People thinks that if my country’s GDP is increasing than we are superpower. Nope, we’re still third world country unless and until a common man has a happy life where they have good public transport, free water, clean air and places, and organised development. 

4. I feel bad when I see people voting based on caste and specifically states like UP and Bihar which are one of the most poorest, corrupt, far under performing and financially burdened states for our country. 

We compare ourselves to china, but we lack basic antiquates and skills in which Chinese people are ahead and that’s the reason they are far superior. I said everything because I live abroad and when I come here back for visiting my country, I can feel what’s wrong. I noticed all of these things and now I understood why people in other countries think we are still very far behind and why still have a long way to go.

snippet.textDisplay:
India will become a larger economy over time, that's simply time+large population+investments=faster economic activity. But will it have exponential growth from 2030-2070? Probably not. Goldmans Sachs are working with incomplete data, and the future is impossible to predict. So will India have higher quality goods and more exports? Yes, but to which degree depends largely on the political leadership and the cultural willingness to adapt to new modes of living. 

As a side note, I would just like to add that this video uses outdated and selective data for digital adoption and manufactured goods. I'm sure the video creator has a good reason for doing this in telling his story, but you can easily find a more complete picture yourself if you look up Digital Adoption Index or Industrial Production Index (a many more datasets that go deeper from macro to microeconomics). And just as young demographics can be both a blessing and a curse depending on the education and healthcare capabilities of the country, so too can specialization and diversification both lead to boom-bust cycles and stagnation. Specialization in a handful of sectors can be a viable strategy, to a certain extent, just not only in one or two so that a market crash destroys the national economy (see Greece with tourism+shipping or Iceland with financial services).

snippet.textDisplay:
china's model of economic growth is akin to a house of cards; easy to rise, easy to fall. Propped up largely by excessive, unsustainable, often unnecessary infrastructure projects. 
If the current real estate bubble, growing unemployment, failure of OBOR and other financial problems such as those of Evergrande are any indication, all of it is set to come to head soon.

Having a more stable & sustained, albeit slower growth rate is suitable for a nation like India. We can raise our economy, social security and standard of living one brick at a time, with a strong foundation. 

In this scenario, it's better to be the wise tortoise, than the drugged-up rabbit.

snippet.textDisplay: any chart/graph prior to 2022 that shows china overtaking the us economy (or remaining larger than india’s for much longer) is laughable at this point. china’s in the same position today that japan was at the beginning of the 90’s, but worse. they’ve reached their economic high water mark and are now a declining power and economy that likely has no realistic path to turn that around within the next few decades. they have too many engrained structural, economic and demographic problems to overcome the slump anytime soon, it’ll only worsen. the us will almost certainly remain the worlds largest economy for the foreseeable future, with india likely becoming a close number two and china a distant third at best.

India, with its vast and diverse population, is making significant strides on the global economic stage. With policies aimed at fostering innovation, entrepreneurship, and sustainable development, India is poised to achieve unparalleled growth in the coming years. 🚀 Explore the incredible economic transformation that India is currently experiencing and delve into the factors that make India a formidable contender to surpass China's economic prowess. Discover the key elements contributing to India's economic boom, including: Robust Demographics, Innovation and Technology, Infrastructure Development, Global Trade, and Investment. 📊 Find out why India's economy is on track to become prosperous! #IndiaEconomy #EconomicGrowth #IndiaVsChina #Innovation #Sustainability #GlobalEconomy
